answers.body_markdown:
A `NoSuchElementException` will be thrown already by `scan.next()` if there is no next element. As you are not checking for `hasNext()` but for `!hasNext()` there is no guard to this.

I didn&#39;t try but this should work:

```
int handleIntVal(Scanner scan) {
    while (scan.hasNext() &amp;&amp; !scan.hasNextInt()) {
        scan.next();
    }
    if (scan.hasNext()) {
        return scan.nextInt();
    }
    return &lt;Whatever your fallback is&gt;;
}
```

What will this code

    while (!scan.hasNextInt()) {
        scan.next();
    }

do when you pass it &quot;a b c&quot;?

It will go 

* &quot;a&quot; is not an `int`, get the next token
* &quot;b&quot; is not an `int`, get the next token
* &quot;c&quot; is not an `int`, get the next token
* There&#39;s no more token left, throw a `NoSuchElementException`.

